35519.object_definition_value: Succession disputes between the sons of Kodros in Athens result in some of them leading a large scale migration across the Aegean, perhaps stopping at Naxos on the way, and founding new cities in Anatolia. The leader of this migration is sometimes said to be Neileus, the founder claimed by Miletos, and sometimes said to be Androklos, the founder claimed by Ephesos. The composition of the accompanying large group is described variously by the different sources.

35519.object_definition_value: Having been sent as an offering to Delphi by the Epigonoi, Manto is instructed to go to Kolophon or Klaros, depending on the version. Teiresias may or may not travel with her, depending on if he has already died in the version. Manto founds both the city and the sanctuary, names them, and gives birth to her son Mopsos there, who is either said to be the son of Apollo or of Rhakios/Lakios (who in some versions Manto meets in Anatolia and marries). Manto and Mopsos are here at the end of the Trojan War, when Calchas and his companions visit and challenge Mopsos to a competition of prophetic skill.

35519.object_definition_value:
In Pindar, Deukalion and Pyrrha came down Mount Parnassos, and as ordered by Zeus settled in Opous and founded the first people, the Lelegians. Pindar makes further reference to the city of Opous as the city of Protogeneia, daughter of Deukalion.

Dionysios of Halikarnassos narrates that the Lelegians (now called Lokrians), together with Curetes (now called Aitolians), and led by Deukalion, expelled the previous settlers of Thessaly and other settlers of Parnassus, and took over the area.

In Pliny, the Epiknemedian Lokrians were formerly known as Leleges.

In the entry of Stephanos Byzantinos, Physkos is the son of Deukalion and the ancestor of the Leleges, now called Lokrians.

Pausanias passage does not evoke direct claims of the Lokrians descending from the Lelegians. Yet we do read that the Opountians claim to house the burial monument of Prometheus, whose mythology is in many ways linked with the creation of the first peoples and, in some sources, his genealogy linked with that of Deuaklion and Pyrrha. https://manto.unh.edu/viewer.p/60/2616/object/6580-8189357

35519.object_definition_value:
The Lokrian hero Aias raped the Trojan Princess Cassandra in Athena's sanctuary during Troy's sack. The goddess, together with Poseidon, decided to avenge Aias, his fellow Lokrians and all the Achaeans while on their return home (nostoi).

In Odyssey, we read that Aias never made it back home (dysnostos). After a sea storm, Aias was driven to the Gyraean Rocks (between the islands of Tinos and Mykonos) before eventually drowning in the sea.

In Euripides's Troades, a vivid dialogue between the goddess Athena and the god Poseidon inform us about the tragic event of Cassandras's rape and represent the anger of the gods who decide to avenge the act while Aias and the Achaeans sail back home.

The myth is repeated with further details in two fragments of Kallimachos. Aias's corpse was washed ashore on the island of Delos, where Thetis found and buried him. The two fragments also inform us of the ritual of the Lokrian Maidens, which was initiated as part of the atonement for Aias's crime.

In Philostratos, we read a completely different version of Aias's behaviour during the Trojan War. Philostratos contradicts earlier myths that say Aias raped Kassandra, and instead, he argues that Aias did not rape her but dragged her from the temple to his tent as war booty. Agamemnon, jealous of her beauty, wanted to keep her as his own trophy. The story suspiciously resembles the known myth of conflict between Achilles and Agamemnon over Brisieis. The author continues on to say that Agamemnon framed Aias, spreading rumours that he raped her and that oracles dictated he had to be punished or all Greeks would have to pay the price. Aias ran away with a small boat during a stormy night and drowned in the sea close to the Gyrades rocks. Unlike other myths, Philostratos presents all the Greeks grieving for the death of a good soldier and vividly describes the funeral rites Aias received.

35519.object_definition_value:
In the Iliad, the spirit of Patroclus visits Achilles to ease his grief and to ask him to have his body buried next to his. Patroclus' narrates the first time he met Achilles, when his father Menoitios brought him to the house of King Peleus in Phthia, where he became Achilles's squire. Before the Trojan War, Achilles makes promises to Menoitios to return his son safe in Opous.

The same Homeric passage is quoted by Aeschines. Strabo too quotes Homer to say that the city of Opous was the birthplace of Patroclus before he was expelled to Phthia. Although Patroclus has to leave, Menoitios stays in Opous. 

Pseudo-Apollosodros also summarizes the reason Patroclus had to run away from Opous and look for shelter in Phthia.

Lastly, Ovid in narrating cases of fugitives and exiles, mentions the case of Patroclus.

35519.object_definition_value:
In Homer's catalogue of ships, the hero Aias is not associated with a specific town. We are told that the Lokrians dwelt in eight towns by the Euboean Gulf. The list includes settlements both in Opountian and Epiknemedian Lokris (East Lokris), but no mention is made of West Lokris.
In the Euripidian catalogue, Aias and the Lokrian fleet sail from the port of Thronio to the port of Aulis, where the Achaean fleets assemble before embarking on the Trojan War.
In Hyginus, Aias and his fleet are also accompanied by the nymph Rhene.

35519.object_definition_value:
Lokros is presented here as the son of king Phaiax of the island of Corfu. After a dispute with his brother, Lokros selects a group of people and goes to settle in Italy.
In Italy, he is the guest-friend of Lakinos, the king of Italians, and marries his daughter Laurine.
The hero Herakles kills Lakinos and accidentally his friend Lokros, too. Herakles buries him and in this place, orders the foundation of the city in his name (Lokri Epizephyrioi).

35519.object_definition_value:
In Pseudo-Skymnos, Ozolian Lokrians were settlers that came from East Lokris (the Lokrians that faced the Euboean Gulf).

Strabo (9.4.9), drawing on the homonymous towns of Alope in Lokri and Phthia, informs us that the Lokri Epizephyrioi in Italy was founded by the Western/Ozolian Lokrians, who were in turn founded by the Epiknemedian Lokrians.

35519.object_definition_value:
Strabo writes that Lokri Epizephyrioi was founded by the hero Evanthes and Lokrians who live close to the Corinthian Gulf (Western Lokrians). He contradicts an earlier account by Ephoros, who suggested Opountian foundation.
In 9.4.9, drawing on the homonymous towns of Alope in Lokri and Phthia, informs us that the Lokri Epizephyrioi in Italy was founded by the Western/Ozolian Lokrians, who were in turn founded by the Epiknemedian Lokrians.

Pseudo-Skymnos mentions both known versions of either Ozolian or Opountian foundation. He also mentions that Epizephyrian Lokrians were the first to write down laws (origins of social practice).

35519.object_definition_value:
The people of Amphissa claimed they were Aetolians to avoid the embarrassing name "Ozolians", although they were originally Lokrians.

Amphissa takes its name from the lover of Apollo, who was the daughter of Macar, son of Aeolus. According to Pausanias, there was also a burial monument dedicated to her in the city.

Harpokration cites Aristotle who supports that the founder of the city was Andraimon, while the city's name is due to the fact that it is surrounded by mountains.

Lokrian nostoi: Thoas, a Trojan hero from Amphissa, seems to be one of the few Lokrians who made it back home from war. It is said that he brought as war booty the bronze image of goddess Athena, which, at the time of Pausanias, was placed and worshipped in a temple on the Acropolis. Pausanias, however, is not convinced by this myth.

35519.object_definition_value:
The name Naupaktos is given from the practice of building ships.

Strabo presents a myth according to which the Herakleides/Dorians built their ships there. He also cites an alternative myth by Ephoros, according to which ships were built there by Lokrians even before the time of Herakleides. Pausanias also says that the Dorians/Herakleides built their ship in Naupaktos before going down to the Peloponnese.
Pseudo-Apollodoros repeats that the name derives from the practice of building ships.

The practice of honouring Hercules as a hero, originates from Mount Oeta, and then followed by Menoitios in Opous and repeated yearly according to his command. Thebans too followed the same practice.
Affiliation of the Opountian Lokrians with the hero Hercules is also evident in the foundation myth of Abdera.

In Apollodorus' Argonautica, Menoitios, son of Aktor, was sent from Opous to join the Argonautic expedition. So too did the heroes Eurytion and Oileus.

In fragments of the Orphic Argonautica, we read again that the heroes Eurition (son of Aktor and king of Phthia), Menoitios and Oileos (both from Opous) joined the expedition.

35519.object_definition_value:
Polybios presents two contradictory versions given by Aristotle and Timaeus regarding the foundation and origins of Lokri Epizephyrioi. He strongly supports the version of Aristotle and suggests that the Lokrians of Italy do so too. When he refers to the Lokris of Greece, he does not make specific mention of either East or West Lokris.

According to Polybios, the Lokrians of Italy claim matrilinear noble origins from the 100 Houses. Quoting Aristotle, he explains that the reason for migration was the romantic relationship between Lokrian women and their slaves. Lokri epizephyrioi was, thus, a colony of expelled women, slaves, and their illegitimate children. The settlers appropriated the Lokrian name and claimed shared origin, and even revied traditional affiliations such as long-standing friendships and alliances of the Lokrians. On the other hand, Timaeus account does not support the story of expelled slaves and instead argues for legitimate freemen who retained relations to their homeland.

35519.object_definition_value:
When the Lokrian women and slaves first arrived to settle in Italy, they had to make an agreement with the native Sicels who inhabited the land and promised they would maintain friendly relations and share the territory with them. However, they tricked them into a false oath and soon expelled them from the area. 

But the Lokrians also adopted several rites of the Sicels, especially the cult practice of Phialophoros.

object.object_name: Formal naming of Ozolian Lokrians (West Lokris)

35544.object_definition_value: Formal naming of Ozolian Lokrians (West Lokris)

object_definition_value: aims to explain an ancient relationship between communities NOT based on kinship
aims to explain the geneaological origins of people or a putative kinship relationship

35519.object_definition_value:
Strabo attributes the name Ozolian (coming from "ozein"=to smell) to the smell of a malodorous and clotted spring that flew down from the hill Taphiasus, at the top of which were the tombs of Nessus and other Centaurs.

Plutarch presents different versions of the name "Ozolians". The first one is again attributed to Nessus; The second to the serpent Python whose body rotted away in the country of the Lokrians; The third one, because these Lokrians wore fleeces and goatskins, lived close with herds of goats and hence smelled alike; The fourth version is the only one talking of a pleasant smell, coming from the odour of the many flowers flourishing in the country. 

Pausanias also presents different versions of the name "Ozolians".

The first story links the Lokrians to Oresthes, son of Deukalion, who planted a wooden stick in the Lokrian soil and knots (ozoi) branched. In other sources too, Lokrians claim affiliation and/or origins with Deukalion.
The other two stories attribute the name to a bad smell in the atmosphere of the whole country, coming either from the rotten corpse of Nessus or the exhalations of a river. Lastly, the name is attributed to the native ancestors of western Lokrians, who did not yet know how to properly weave garments and wore untanned animal skins and fleeces, which made their skin smell horrible.

In another passage of Pausanias (10.38.8), we read that the Lokrians of Amphissa claimed they were Aetolians as they were ashamed of the name "Ozolians".

35519.object_definition_value:
There are two versions of the formal naming Kalliaros.

The first comes from the eponymous hero, Kalliaros, who was the son of Hodoidokos and Laonome. From other sources, we know that Hodoidokos was the son of Kynos, brother of Larymna, and grandson of Opous (other eponymous heroes of Lokrian towns). (Eustathius on Homer, p. 227). These myths link the Lokrian towns through shared genealogies of eponymous heroes.

In the second version, the name Kalliaros derives from the easily cultivable land.

There are no information from where did Sagaris depart from Italy - only that he was accompanied by Troezinians who inhabited an area of Argolis (Peloponnese).

Lokrian foundation of Sybaris is also recorded by Antonius Liberalis.

35519.object_definition_value:
Herakles is the protagonist of this poem, which narrates his expedition against Kyknos, son of Ares, who challenged the hero to battle when he was crossing through Thessaly.

The poem starts with Amphitryon's task to avenge the death of his future wife, Alcmene, who will later give birth to Herakles and Iphikles in Thebes.
Boeotians, Lokrians, and Phokinas come to the aid of Amphitryon and remain his allies throughout the poem. 

The rivalry with Thessalians reflected in the poem might be related to the First Sacred War(595-585 BCE).

object.object_name: Daphnous and the division of East Lokris

35544.object_definition_value: Daphnous and the division of East Lokris

object_definition_value: aims to explain the geneaological origins of people or a putative kinship relationship

35519.object_definition_value:
Strabo explains that Daphnous, located at the exit of the Dipotamos corridor that linked the Kephissos valley to the Euboean Gulf, was once a Phokian city before being razed to the ground by the Lokrians. Phokian identity is claimed through a burial monument in the city which the story tells belongs to Schedios, the leader of the Phokians in the Trojan war.

At some unknown point in history, Phokians had occupied the Dipotamos corridor and hence, Strabo explains, divided East Lokris into two parts, the Opountian and the Epiknemedian. At the time of Strabo, Lokrians had claimed back their territory.

35519.object_definition_value:
According to Strabo (13.1.3), Cleues, son of Dorus, together with Malaus, both descendants of Agamemnon, found the city of Kyme Phrykonis in Aiolis. Before this, they spent a lot of time in Lokris and Mount Phrykio, after which they named the city.

In 13.3.3, Strabo explains that people set out from Mount Phrykio (a Lokrian mountain above Thermopylae), and arrived in Aiolis. There, they first occupied the Acropolis of Larisa, taking it over by the Pelasgians, who were exhausted after the Trojan War. They then moved on and found Kyme, where they settled the rest of the people remaining.

In mythology, Protogeneia is the name of both the daughter of Deukalion and Pyrrha, and the daughter of Opous the elder (from Elis).
